I'll also note that what you describe, when used to describe information technology instead of heavy industry, sounds a lot like the reason the Soviet Union fell. Gorbachev knew that the reason for the west's success was the dissemination of information, and that if he didn't open up the Soviet Union to the free flow of information, they'd be left in the dust technologically. He thought he could control the opening of the society in a way that it could stay Soviet while people interacted more freely. Unfortunately for him, once the process started it snowballed. He probably could've stopped it if he instituted harsh, Stalinist policies, but he didn't have it in him. Instead of a civil war, he got a collapsed government.
